ce for the lived experience of medieval monasticism.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aMedieval Sources 2021. 4aMedieval Studies 2020. 7aHISTORY / Medieval.2bisacsh  aChronicles.  aGermany.  aHirsau.  aInvestiture.  aLived experience.  aMonasticism.  aPetershausen.  aReform.  aSociety.  aSwabia.1 aBeach, Alison I., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBeach, Alison I., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLi, Shannon M. T., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLi, Shannon M.T., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSutherland, Samuel S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSutherland, Samuel, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2020 eBook-Packagez978311128248040uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152612679540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526126795423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526126795/original  a978-3-11-128248-0  Manchester University Press 2020 eBook-Packageb2020  aGBV-deGruyter-alles